otswana -- t“Traditional Authority” and Governance in the Emjindini Royal Swazi Chiefdom, Barberton, Mpumalanga -- tWidening the Democracy Debate: Bogosi and Ethnicity in Botswana -- tThe Role of the House of Chiefs (Ntlo ya Dikgosi) in Botswana -- tThe National House of Chiefs – Ghana -- tThe Role of Traditional Leaders in the Administration of Customary Courts in Botswana -- tThe Secular Dynamics of Traditional Leadership in KwaZulu-Natal, South Africa: The Decade of Active Political Transformation after Apartheid -- tContesting the Political Meaning of Chieftaincies in the New South Africa -- tWechiau Hippo Sanctuary: Contributions of Ghana’s Traditional Leaders to Partnership Success with the Calgary Zoo, Canada -- tDikgosi and the Politics of Land in Botswana -- tConclusions -- tGlossary -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of essays examines the relatively new, and frequently overlooked, political phenomenon in post-colonial Africa of chieftaincy "re-inventing" itself. The traditional authority of chiefs has been one of Africa's missing voices who are now bringing new resources to the challenges that AIDS, gender, governance, and development pose to the peoples of Africa. Reinventing African Chieftaincy in the Age of AIDS, Gender, Governance, and Development presents new research in Ghana, Botswana, and South Africa, providing the broadest geographic African coverage on the topic of African chieftaincy. The nineteen authors, many of them emerging scholars from Africa, are all members of the Traditional Authority Applied Research Network (TAARN). Their essays give critical insight into the transformation processes of chieftaincy from the end of the colonial/apartheid periods to the present. They also examine the realities of male and female traditional leaders in reinventing their legitimacy and their political offices in the age of great social and political unrest, health issues and governance and development challenges. With contribtutions by: Kusi Ankra Sherri A. Brown Wilhelmina J. Donkoh Gaelle Eizlini Brian Keating Kereng Daniel Lebogang Kgotleng Mogopodi H. Lekorwe Sibongiseni Mkhize Mpho F. Moloma Morgan Nyendu Christiane Owusu-Sarpong Donald I. Ray Kimberley Schoon Keshav C. Sharma Mpilo Pearl Sithole Robert Thornton Shahid Vawda  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChiefdoms -- Botswana. 0aChiefdoms -- Ghana. 0aChiefdoms -- South Africa. 0aGhana -- Politics and government. 0aTribal government -- Botswana. 0aTribal government -- Ghana. 0aTribal government -- South Africa. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh1 aAnkra, Kusi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Sherri A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Sherri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Tacita A.O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Tacita, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDonkah, W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonkoh, Wilhelmina J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEizlini, Gaelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeating, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKgotleng, K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKgotleng, Kereng Daniel Lebogang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLekorwe, M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLekorwe, Mogopodi H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1